-- Chalco, Guotai Junan, Huadian, Merchants Bank: Hong Kong Equities Preview
-- Ronnie Koo
-- 2010-07-08T01:22:23Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-08/chalco-guotai-junan-huadian-power-hong-kong-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The  following  companies may have
significant price changes in Hong Kong trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  
 The  Hang Seng Index  fell 1.1 percent to 19,857.07.  The Hang
Seng China Enterprises Index , which tracks so-called H shares of
Chinese companies, dropped 1.3 percent to 11,305.18.  
 Aluminum Corp. of China Ltd.  (2600 HK): The company’s
parent, Aluminum Corp. of China, also known as Chinalco, is said
to have indicated an interest in buying a minority stake in the
Mongolian Oyu Tolgoi project, according to a statement from
Ivanhoe Mines Ltd. Chinalco is the nation’s biggest producer of
aluminum. Chalco dropped 1.7 percent to HK$5.89.  
 China Merchants Bank Co. Ltd.  (3968 HK): The Chinese lender
said first-half net income will increase more than 50 percent
compared with a year earlier. Merchants Bank, China’s fifth-
biggest lender, fell 0.9 percent to HK$18.36.  
 China Petroleum & Chemical Corp.  (386 HK): The company,
also known as Sinopec, cut crude processing volume at its Yangzi
oil refinery in the eastern Jiangsu province on refining losses
and weaker demand, a plant official said. Sinopec, China’s
largest oil refiner, fell 1.9 percent to HK$6.23.  
 Guotai Junan International Holdings Ltd.  (1788 HK): The
brokerage sold 410 million shares at HK$4.30 each, raising net
proceeds of HK$1.66 billion ($213 million) in an initial public
offering, according to a statement. Trading starts today.  
 HSBC Holdings Plc  (5 HK): The bank is in the early stages
of assessing a bid for Nedbank Group Ltd., majority owned by Old
Mutual Plc, Sky News reported, without attribution.  
 Separately, units of HSBC were sued by U.S. customers who
said the bank’s credit-card payment-protection service defrauds
disabled, retired and unemployed consumers, according to
complaints filed July 2 against HSBC units in federal courts in
Philadelphia and Camden, New Jersey. HSBC, Europe’s biggest
lender by market value, retreated 0.6 percent to HK$71.20.  
 Huadian Power International Corp.  (1071 HK): The
electricity producer said first-half power generation rose 25
percent to 62.52 million MWh from a year earlier. The stock
dipped 0.5 percent to HK$1.87.  
